Ecological Indicators

Volume 160, March 2024, 111877

Camera trapping and telemetry for detecting and quantifying animal interactions: Not anything goes

Author links open overlay panel, , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ecolind.2024.111877Get rights and content
Under a Creative Commons license
open access

Highlights

  • •
    Camera Trapping Resource Monitoring shows high ability to detect animal interactions.
  • •
    Environment and species ecology limit the feasibility of Resource Monitoring.
  • •
    Regular Grid Camera Trapping is able to identify which species are interacting.
  • •
    Quantification of interactions by Regular Grid Camera Trapping should be avoided.
  • •
    Telemetry at high fixation rates shows great performance in detecting interactions.

Abstract

Telemetry using Global Positioning Systems (GPS) and camera trapping are two widely used approaches to detect animal interactions involving wildlife. However, while the former follows an individual-based approach, the latter follows a population-based approach, which may lead to different outcomes when describing interaction networks. In this study, we compared the performance of GPS telemetry, regular grid camera trapping (CT-RG), and resource monitoring camera trapping (in which cameras are placed monitoring a valuable resource for animals, such as water or food; CT-RM) in detecting and quantifying animal interactions. We used spatially explicit simulated trajectories of 150 individuals of 3 imaginary species. We simulated 9 different scenarios of resource visiting frequency and spatial resource aggregation in the environment to assess the potential influence of animal behavior and landscape structure. The simulated trajectories were sampled using the three approaches with six different sampling efforts each, and the direct and indirect interactions between the three species were quantified. Additionally, CT-RG and CT-RM were applied in Doñana National Park to evaluate their differences and limitations in field application. In terms of simulation, CT-RM offered the best performance in detecting direct interactions, and GPS achieved good performance when using a high number of fixes per hour. Both CT-RM and GPS also achieved good performance in detecting indirect interactions. CT-RG, on the other hand, missed most direct and indirect interactions, but correctly identified the pairs of species that interacted indirectly at some point. In the field trial, CT-RM and CT-RG detected almost the same number of species pairs interacting indirectly. However, CT-RG missed at least half of the species pairs that interacted directly. The spatial aggregation of the resource favors the performance of GPS over CT-RM, while the opposite occurs when the frequency of animal visits to the resource increases. To summarize, CT-RM is the most reliable method for detecting interactions when resource monitoring is feasible (e.g., small ponds in arid areas). Otherwise, GPS may show better performance, although it may miss direct interactions if a high fix rate is not used. Finally, the use of CT-RG should be limited to identify which species could potentially interact indirectly, but not to quantify these interactions.

1. Introduction

The study of spatial interactions between wild animals and with livestock is of great importance for ecological (such as predation, reproduction, social relationships, or group dynamics; Latham et al., 2011, Mejia Salazar et al., 2016, Spiegel et al., 2020), and epidemiological purposes, as they can involve pathogen transmission (Bacigalupo et al., 2020). From the epidemiological point of view, we can differentiate direct interactions, which involve proximate contact between individuals, and indirect interactions, where transmission may be mediated by the environment and/or a vector (Craft, 2015). The study of interactions is crucial to identify which species may be involved in the spatio-temporal dynamics of pathogens, as well as their relevance (Ferreira et al., 2023, Manlove et al., 2022).
The methodologies used to study interactions involving wildlife are typically individual-based, following a Lagrangian perspective, in which the sampling device moves with the individual (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2021). Individual-level obtained information can be scaled up to population-level patterns to answer ecological and epidemiological questions (Mueller and Fagan, 2008, Phillips et al., 2019). Global Positioning Systems telemetry (GPS) and/or proximity loggers are the survey approaches most frequently used for epidemiological purposes, although the latter is mostly limited to the detection of direct interactions (Drewe et al., 2012, Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2019). These methodologies require capturing individuals, which implies invasiveness, animal welfare issues, and costly and time-consuming procedures (Shimada et al., 2020), being especially constrained when working with endangered, small and/or elusive species (He et al., 2022). Camera trapping, on the other hand, is a population-based sampling approach that follows a Eulerian perspective, i.e., the sampling devices are in a fixed location where animals may occur eventually (Bassing et al., 2023, Phillips et al., 2019). Its use in wildlife monitoring has increased over the recent years, primarily because it is a mostly noninvasive procedure and its ability to detect elusive species (Delisle et al., 2021). Camera trapping has been used mainly in ecological studies, such as behavior, activity patterns, habitat selection and use, territory occupancy, scavenging, or competition for resources, among others (Burton et al., 2015). Camera trapping has also been used for the detection of interactions between animals for ecological purposes, such as group or predator–prey relationships, as well as epidemiological studies, such as interactions between wildlife and livestock (Kukielka et al., 2013, Niedballa et al., 2019, Smith et al., 2020). Most studies focused on epidemiological interests usually place camera traps in locations where the occurrence of an interaction is deemed most probable or where it can be detected (camera trapping for resource monitoring; CT-RM), such as in feeding or watering points, as well as probable entry zones to a farm (Bacigalupo et al., 2022, Kukielka et al., 2013, Payne et al., 2016, Varela-Castro et al., 2021). The increasing use of camera trapping, coupled with citizen science, is also leading to large-scale datasets encompassing a wide variety of species and locations (Green et al., 2022, Hsing et al., 2022). However, camera trapping sampling designs often require a random deployment of cameras within the study area (see e.g., Rowcliffe et al., 2008), for instance, based on regular grid pattern (CT-RG; Rowcliffe et al., 2008). The amount of information generated by CT-RG has led to its use also for the detection and quantification of animal interactions for epidemiological purposes (Barroso et al., 2023, Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020;b).
Recent comparative studies of Lagrangian and Eulerian perspectives have shown that they yield different results when estimating different ecological parameters (Bassing et al., 2023, Ferrer-Ferrando et al., 2023). While GPS has been considered the reference methodology for calculating animal interactions, its performance has not yet been compared with CT-RM. Additionally, a proper evaluation remains unknown when comparing against CT-RG (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020b). These comparisons are challenging, as they require us to know the actual number of interactions between individuals. In this regard, spatially explicit simulations of animal trajectories are often used to test behavioral hypotheses of wildlife under controlled conditions (Gurarie et al., 2015, Palencia et al., 2021a). We used this simulation approach to evaluate the performance of these three approaches, GPS, CT-RG, and CT-RM, in the detection and quantification of interactions between pairs of species. Additionally, we evaluated how the animal behavior and the environment affect the performance of each approach. Finally, CT-RG and CT-RM were applied simultaneously for the quantification of interactions among wild mammals in the Doñana National Park (DNP) to verify whether the differences revealed between both approaches through simulation were also evident with real data, as well as to identify their limitations under field conditions.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Performance evaluation using simulations

We used spatially explicit simulations of animal trajectories. In these simulations, we assumed that animals moved in an environment of 40 km2 including 30 locations of a resource they needed to visit at a certain frequency, which could be interpreted as a water point or a feeding site, for example (Payne et al., 2016). In each step of the simulation, the animals move a distance given by a Gamma function and turn an angle given by a Cauchy distribution. The animals could exhibit three different behaviors for moving within a randomly shaped home range: slow and tortuous Brownian motion (associated with foraging), fast and less tortuous Brownian motion (associated with transit), or fast and directed movement toward the resource (associated with a discharged state, in which the animal needs to visit the resource to recharge). The need to visit the resource was controlled by a recharge-and-discharge model (Hooten et al., 2019), where the animal progressively discharges at each simulation step and recharges upon visiting the resource (see Fig. 1).
We simulated three fictional species (A, B and C) with different home range sizes, movement speed, tortuosity, probability of behavior change, and resource needs for each one (see Table 1). These parameters can affect the proportion of interactions that occur at the resource compared to those that occur at a random location, and therefore, they can influence the performance of the approaches. Consequently, we simulated three scenarios with different charge and discharge parameters, providing variability to the number of daily visits of each species to the resource (see Table 2), thus accounting for variability in the proportion of interactions at the resource and outside. Furthermore, the spatial aggregation of the resource in the environment could also affect the performance of the respective approaches. Hence, we considered three scenarios of resource aggregation. In the lower aggregation scenario, the resource is evenly distributed (in a regular grid) in the environment, while in the higher aggregation scenario, it is concentrated in two areas (see Table 2). Overall, the experiment resulted in a total of nine scenarios. For each scenario, we simulated 150 animals (50 of each species) over a period of 30 days, at a time interval of 1 fix each 5 min.

Table 1. Parameters used to simulate the trajectories of the three species (A, B, and C). The Gamma function to determine the displacement distance at each step is defined by two parameters: mean and standard deviation (SD). The Cauchy function that determines the turning angle at each step is defined by the concentration parameter (ρ). Lower concentration results in a more tortuous trajectory. At each step, animals have a defined probability of changing behavior (P.) between ‘Transit’ and ‘Foraging’. When an animal is close to discharge, it moves towards the closest resource to recharge. Each step is 5 min.

Since individual identification is not always possible in camera trapping (Caravaggi et al., 2017), we only considered interspecific interactions. To calculate the total number of interactions among all simulated animals, an interaction was recorded when at least two individuals were 10 m apart or less, either at the same time for direct interactions or within a 48-hour temporal window for indirect interactions.

2.1.1. Quantifying interactions by GPS telemetry

To quantify interactions using GPS telemetry, we simulated marking 10 randomly selected animals of each species. We considered six efforts in GPS location recording (see Table 3). The random sampling was repeated 10 times for each scenario and effort, totaling 540 databases of marked individuals (9 scenarios, 6 efforts, and 10 repetitions). An interaction was considered to occur under the same criteria as previously for the overall individuals.

2.1.2. Quantifying interactions by camera trapping

We considered the placement of cameras on a regular grid (CT-RG), the placement of cameras monitoring randomly selected resource locations (CT-RM), and the combination of both approaches. We considered six efforts in terms of the number of cameras (see Table 3) and repeated the sampling 10 times for each sampling effort and scenario, totaling 540 image databases for each approach. We considered a simulated animal to be captured by a camera trap when its trajectory intersected a square buffer of 5 m around each camera location, resulting in a detection area of 100 m2 for each camera (Palencia et al., 2021b). Since we are working under the assumption of no possible individual identification, we established a threshold of two time steps (10 min) for the time that must elapse between two images of individuals of the same species to be considered distinct detections (Kukielka et al., 2013). An interaction was considered to occur when two individuals were detected by the same camera, being direct if detected at the same time and indirect if detected within a 48-hour time window.

2.1.3. Comparison of performance among approaches

The detected interactions were summarized in a single database. For each of the 9 scenarios, 4 approaches (GPS, CT-RG, CT-RM, and the two camera trapping approaches combined), 6 sampling efforts, and 10 repetitions, the number of direct and indirect interactions was calculated for each of the 6 possible interspecific pairs: A-B, A-C, B-A, B-C, C-A, C-B, totaling 12,960 records. The species before the hyphen represents the one which visits the location where the interaction occurs first (depositor), and the one after the hyphen represents the one which visits it later (acquirer). These approaches only sample a part of the population (GPS) or the territory (CT-RG and CT-RM), so the real number of interactions in the entire population and territory is unknown unless extrapolations are made (Bohm et al., 2009, Yang et al., 2023). However, the number of detected interactions can indeed be considered as a predictor of the total number of interactions that actually occur (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020b). Consequently, we assessed the performance in detecting and quantifying animal interactions of the four approaches by modeling the real number of interactions between each pair of species, assuming it to follow a Poisson distribution, and using the number of detected interactions for each pair of species as predictor. We performed the modeling independently for direct and indirect interactions, for each approach and for each sampling effort, totaling 48 models (4 approaches times 6 efforts, both for direct and indirect interactions). The goodness of fit of the model, measured by the R2, indicates how well the proportion of detected interactions between each species pair fits the one that actually takes place. The reason for following this procedure is that one method may detect more interactions than another, but fails to detect the proportion of interactions between each pair of species, thus failing to identify those species that may play a greater role in the spread of the disease. In addition, the number of missing pairs (i.e., the number of interacting pairs of species in which no interaction was detected) was also calculated for each approach and sampling effort.

2.1.4. Factors influencing performance

The frequency with which animals need to visit the resource, as well as the spatial aggregation of the resource in the environment, are factors that can influence the performance of the approaches. This is because CT-RM only captures events at the resource, and CT-RG only captures events in certain locations that do not include the resource (except if, by chance, some cameras in the grid coincide with the resource). To analyze their effect on the performance of each approach, the total number of detected interactions was modeled, assuming that it follows a negative binomial distribution (given the overdispersion of the data; Zuur et al., 2009) using approach, sampling effort, resource visit frequency, and spatial aggregation of the resource in the environment as predictors. The latter three were considered as ordered factors since their values follow a non-linear progression. The inclusion of these factors allows us to control the number of detected interactions that would be expected if the relationship between the approach and the other factors were constant. Therefore, the interactions of the approach with the sampling effort, resource visit frequency, and resource aggregation were also included, aiming to determine if they are related differently to each method. Direct and indirect interactions were modeled separately.

2.2. Estimation of interactions with camera traps under field conditions

2.2.1. Study area

The field study was carried out in an area within the Doñana National Park (DNP) in southwestern Spain (37°09′ N, 6°09′ W), a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve of 542.52 km2. The DNP is known for its remarkable biodiversity and comprises different habitats such as seasonal marshland in the eastern part, scrublands in the western part, and sand dunes in the south. Within the park, there are three wild ungulate species: red deer (Cervus elaphus), fallow deer (Dama dama), and wild boar (Sus scrofa), and several wild carnivores, such as red fox (Vulpes vulpes), European badger (Meles meles), Egyptian mongoose (Herpestes ichneumon), genet (Genetta genetta), wildcat (Felis silvestris) and Iberian lynx (Lynx pardinus). The park is also home to extensively managed horses and to a native breed of cattle known as ‘marismeña’, which is also raised under extensive conditions throughout the year, except for periodic veterinary inspections. DNP's southwestern border is adjacent to the Atlantic Ocean, resulting in a dry subhumid Mediterranean climate with Atlantic influences with a markedly irregular water supply, which shapes the dynamics of the marshland, leading to seasonal flooding in winter and spring, attracting ungulates to the scrub areas. In the dry season of summer and fall, water sources and meadows become crucial habitats, drawing several species (Barasona et al., 2014a).

2.2.2. Camera trapping

A total of 39 camera traps (Browning Recon Force 4 K Edge) were placed during a period of 104 days between the end of August and mid-December of 2020. The cameras were set to operate all day, recording a burst of four images at each activation, with the minimum triggering interval between activations. They were mounted on metal stakes at a height of 40 to 50 cm above the ground, facing north, and without bait. Of these, 24 cameras were placed on a regular grid with approximately 1 km spacing (CT-RG) and 15 cameras were placed monitoring water sources (CT-RM). During the summer and fall in DNP, water scarcity makes it mainly available in small artificial ponds built for livestock, which can be easily monitored with a single camera, either because the camera's range covers the entire pond or because the entryway to the pond can be monitored. All camera traps were checked every three weeks to change batteries and memory cards.

2.2.3. Quantifying interactions

The number of individuals captured in each image was not counted, considering the group as the epidemiological unit. As with the criterion used in the simulation, we considered consecutive images of the same species with less than 10 min between them as a single detection. A direct interaction between two groups was considered to occur when they were captured by the same camera simultaneously, and an indirect interaction when they were captured in the same camera within a 48-hour temporal window. Birds and small mammals were not considered. Additionally, species that appeared for fewer than 15 distinct days in the images were excluded from the analysis with the aim of avoiding the detection of pairs that involved those species that temporarily passed through the study area, such as the Iberian lynx or the wildcat.

2.2.4. Comparing results

To analyze the differences in results obtained through CT-RG and CT-RM in DNP, we compared: (1) the number of species pairs in which interactions were detected, both direct and indirect; (2) the average number of interactions detected by each camera throughout the study period, and (3) how pairs of interacting species are ordered and how they are grouped based on the number of interactions. For the grouping, we used Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering with a cluster linkage based on minimum within-cluster variance (known as Ward linkage; Murtagh and Contreras, 2017). When determining the cutting height of the tree (i.e., the difference between two groups at which it is decided that they belong to two distinct clusters), it is essential to consider that using a single value for two trees (in this case, CT-RG and CT-RM) based on a non-standardized value, such as the number of interactions, may result in the tree with lower values forming a reduced number of clusters. For this reason, we chose a height of 0.5 times the standard deviation of the detected interactions to compensate for the magnitude of the difference between approaches (Nielsen, 2016). A sensitivity analysis was carried out on the cutting height of the tree by testing 20 heights ranging from 0.05 to 1 time the standard deviation, at 0.05 intervals. The ratio of the number of clusters obtained in both trees (CT-RG and CT-RM) was extracted for each cutting height.

3. Results

3.1. Performance evaluation using simulations

3.1.1. Comparison of performance among approaches

CT-RM resulted as the most reliable method to detect direct interspecific interactions between animals. It exhibited the highest R2 and rarely missed a species pair (see Fig. 2). GPS showed low capabilities in terms of detecting direct interactions at low sampling efforts, missing several pairs of species. However, at high sampling efforts, it successfully identified all interacting pairs in most cases, resulting also in improved accuracy when quantifying differences among species pairs. On the other hand, CT-RG did not detect direct interactions in most cases, demonstrating poor capabilities for this purpose.
All approaches detected all pairs of interacting species in most cases when identifying indirect interactions (see Fig. 2). However, the accuracy in quantifying differences among species pairs varied among the approaches: while GPS and CT-RM exhibited high R2 values, CT-RG showed low values, which means a poor assessment of differences in the number of interactions among species pairs.

3.1.2. Factors influencing performance

The modeling revealed that an increase in the spatial aggregation of the resource in the environment improved the performance of GPS and CT-RG to a greater extent than the performance of CT-RM (see Table 4 and Fig. 3) in the detection of both direct and indirect interactions. However, the increase in the frequency of animal visits to the resource had a much more marked positive effect on the performance of CT-RM than on the other approaches used. Finally, GPS is the method that benefits the most from the increase in the sampling effort. CT-RG, on the other hand, sees only a slight improvement in its performance as a consequence of higher sampling efforts.

3.2. Estimating interactions with camera traps using real data

Eight species were finally considered to quantify interactions in DNP: European badger, cattle, fallow deer, horse, Egyptian mongoose, red deer, red fox, and wild boar, totaling 56 pairs of species when considering interactions in both directions. All pairs were detected interacting indirectly by CT-RM, and only two pairs (badger - mongoose and fallow deer – badger) remained undetected by the CT-RG (see Fig. 4). Forty pairs were also detected interacting directly by CT-RM, but only half of them were detected by CT-RG.
The number of direct and indirect interactions detected by CT-RM exceeded that of CT-RG for most of the study period. The temporal trend also differed between the approaches. The number of indirect interactions (which represented most interactions) detected by CT-RM showed a temporal decrease from August to December, which is not observed in CT-RG (see Fig. 3). The structure of species pairs based on the number of interactions also varied between the approaches, revealing different patterns in the order of species pairs when sorted by the number of interactions. Cluster analysis resulted in a ratio of 0.57 clusters in the CT-RG dataset for each cluster in the CT-RM dataset (4 and 7 clusters respectively; see Fig. 5). The sensitivity analysis to tree cutting height resulted in a mean ratio of 0.58 ± 0.06, indicating that it may affect the number of clusters but not the ratio between approaches.

4. Discussion

In both study scenarios (modelled and real data), monitoring resources through camera trapping (CT-RM) proved to be the most reliable method for detecting direct interactions. Furthermore, its performance in detecting indirect interactions is on par with GPS, which could be considered a reference in such studies (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2021). However, the applicability of CT-RM depends on the environmental conditions and ecology of the species studied (mainly to the availability and distribution of a valuable resource for the species which can be monitored by camera trapping), being GPS less sensitive to these conditions. CT-RG proved to be a valid method for detecting which species interact indirectly, but it fails to quantify these interactions, calling for caution when identifying the species with the highest potential for disease transmission.

4.1. On the simulation

The results vary significantly when detecting direct or indirect interactions. CT-RM was the most effective method to detect direct interactions. Even with the lowest sampling efforts, it rarely fails to detect one of the interacting pairs of species (see Fig. 2). On the other hand, CT-RG is barely able to detect direct interactions, even with the highest sampling efforts. Camera trapping has temporal continuity, but lacks spatial continuity, so the location of the cameras is key for its performance. GPS shows low performance in the detection of direct interactions when the fix interval is wide. In fact, at the lowest sampling efforts, it may even fail to detect any. This is because direct interactions in the simulation, as in reality, are usually of short duration (Bohm et al., 2009, Cowie et al., 2015, Lavelle et al., 2016). GPS has spatial continuity, as the individual is sampled regardless of its location, but not temporal continuity, as locations are not continuously recorded. With the reduction of the GPS fix interval, the performance of GPS in detecting direct interactions increases exponentially. However, it is important to consider that a reduced fix interval implies higher battery consumption, which may lead to shorter sampling durations or the use of more expensive and/or heavier devices (Hebblewhite and Haydon, 2010, Shimada et al., 2020).
When it comes to detecting indirect interactions, the picture changes, especially in the detection of pairs of interacting species. All approaches, regardless of the sampling effort, show high performance for this purpose, rarely failing to detect any pair. This is particularly interesting in the case of CT-RG, as it is used in many wildlife-related studies (Rovero et al., 2013), and the already generated information can also be used to identify which species interact indirectly (Barroso et al., 2023, Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020;b). However, its accuracy in quantifying the interactions is poor. On the other hand, GPS and CT-RM show similar performance for this purpose, and much higher than that shown by CT-RG. It is worth noting that the combination of CT-RG and CT-RM appears to provide no added value compared to the information obtained through CT-RM alone, both for direct and indirect interactions. However, the combination of both approaches could help to detect interactions involving species that do not use the monitored resource.
The spatial aggregation of the resource in the environment and the frequency with which individuals visit it should also be considered in the study design. An increase in the visit frequency (for instance, to water in summer) enhances the performance of CT-RM compared to the other approaches evaluated, as expected, since a higher number of visits result in a greater number of interactions at the resource, and these are detected by this method. However, the spatial aggregation of the resource favors GPS and CT-RG performance over CT-RM, probably because, with the resource being more aggregated, animals move in a more constrained, making them more likely to interact outside the resource, and such interaction can be detected by CT-RG or GPS but not by CT-RM. Therefore, in areas where the resource is spatially aggregated and animals visit it infrequently, such as water sources in wet areas (Varela-Castro et al., 2021), GPS may have an advantage over CT-RM. In contrast, in arid areas where water points are scarce and dispersed (Barasona et al., 2014a, Carrasco-Garcia et al., 2015), using CT-RM might be more advantageous. Combining CT-RM with GPS telemetry would be an effective alternative in all scenarios, as it provides complete monitoring of the individuals both at the resource and elsewhere. However, this option comes with high economic and effort costs.

4.2. On the real data

The results obtained from real camera trapping data in DNP support those obtained through the simulation. CT-RM shows greater ability than CT-RG to detect pairs of species interacting directly (see Fig. 4). However, there are minimal differences in the detection of pairs of species when the interaction occurs indirectly. Regarding the quantification of interactions, CT-RM reveals a decline in the number of interactions from late August to December, which had also been previously detected in DNP using GPS (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020a), but it seems undetectable by CT-RG. However, in the temporal pattern of interactions detected by CT-RG, two peaks are observed, corresponding to the weeks when park rangers conducted ungulate population controls (the authors, unpublished data). These controls involve shooting, which can increase animal activity and daily ranges and consequently the likelihood of detection by CT-RG (Laguna et al., 2021a, Laguna et al., 2021b, Picardi et al., 2018). The approaches also diverge when quantifying which pairs of species interact more frequently (see Fig. 5). Under the same clustering criterion, CT-RM forms a larger number of clusters than CT-RG, which signifies a higher resolution in distinguishing between groups of pairs of species according to the number of interactions. Moreover, the order of species pairs based on the total number of interactions differs between approaches, consistent with the simulation results, which had suggested greater reliability for the rankings obtained through CT-RM. Contemporary GPS data for DNP is not available, preventing a direct comparison. Although the results obtained through CT-RM and CT-RG differ from those in previous studies by GPS, the intra- and inter-annual variability in these patterns discourages their comparison (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020;a, Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020;b).
The field application of the CT-RM method reveals additional limitations. In some cases, it is easy to know the location of the resources and monitor them or their access points, such as feeders or artificial water points on farms (Bacigalupo et al., 2022, Campbell et al., 2019, Kukielka et al., 2013, Payne et al., 2016, Varela-Castro et al., 2021). In the case of DNP, the scarcity of water and the presence of artificial ponds for its supplementation make resource monitoring easy (Barasona et al., 2014b). However, studies that exclusively focus on wildlife and/or extensively managed livestock, located in areas with abundant resources or where they are large (such as lakes, meadows, or rivers; e.g. Woodroffe et al., 2016), pose a challenge in identifying and monitoring the key resources, since the detectability area of a camera trap is reduced (Palencia et al., 2021b). Identifying the limiting resource is also crucial. In a wetland, for example, water may not be a limiting resource, but perhaps bedding areas could be. Therefore, when applying CT-RM, it is essential to carefully study which resource to monitor based on the ecology of the species and on the environment in which it is located. Failure to identify the limiting resource would lead to loss of performance. Where there is no limiting resource, GPS and CT-RG should improve their performance compared to CT-RM. Another limitation of CT-RM is the huge amount of images collected, as animals visit resources much more frequently than the random points monitored by regular grid. In this specific case, the 15 cameras monitoring resources over 104 days resulted in more than 1 million images. Processing such large quantities of images is time-consuming, although significant progress is being made in the field of artificial intelligence for automatic image processing (Green et al., 2020, Vélez et al., 2022). However, being a population-based method has certain advantages for camera trapping compared to GPS, which is individual-based. Camera trapping allows us to identify interactions among all species and individuals present in the study area, not just among those we have marked. In addition, GPS requires information about the population, as we will detect more interactions between the species that we mark more individuals of, but these may not be the most abundant in the study area (Triguero-Ocaña et al., 2020a), and marked individuals may not be representative of the population, leading to a failure in identifying the species that interact the most (Gilbertson et al., 2021, He et al., 2022).

4.3. Final remarks

The results, under our simulated and real scenarios for the considered range of sampling efforts, suggest CT-RM as the most reliable method to study the epidemiology of diseases primarily transmitted through direct contact, such as the sarcoptic mange, the African Swine Fever, or the Chronic Wasting Disease studies in certain regions (Escobar et al., 2022, Potapov et al., 2016, Sanchez-Vizcaino et al., 2012). Nevertheless, GPS telemetry when using a reduced fix interval could also work for this purpose. For epidemiological studies on diseases transmitted through indirect interaction, like bovine tuberculosis (Broughan et al., 2016, Walter et al., 2012), both GPS and CT-RM seem to be effective approaches. The choice between one or the other will depend on the budget, the target species (size, detectability, capture feasibility, etc.) and the ability to identify and monitor key resources for animals through camera trapping. The combination of GPS and CT-RM is likely the most effective option for studying animal interactions, but it also involves a high cost in terms of financial resources and effort. On the other hand, CT-RG would be discouraged for epidemiological studies, although data from studies with other purposes can be used to detect pairs of species that may interact.
